-    "recommendation": "Proceed, with the diligence conditional on three things. First, get the revenue-quality split: what share of the $329 million comes from failed versus successful traders, and what the repeat-attempt rate is. That ratio, more than any other number, decides whether this is a durable business or a monetised failure funnel, and it should drive the multiple. Second, build a regulatory scenario model that quantifies group revenue and margin under full brokerage regulation of the evaluation business, and stress the $250 million facility's covenants against a 30% decline in evaluation revenue. Third, obtain OANDA's standalone economics and the true pro-forma blended margin. The group's post-deal margin will land well below 19% by design, and any valuation anchored on historical prop margins will be wrong. This is a strong asset executing a clever hedge. The evidence says FTMO is well run. What remains unanswered is whether $250 million of debt and one acquisition are enough to outrun the regulatory reckoning its own industry is asking for."
